net.sourceforge.waters.model.compiler.instance

Class ModuleInstanceCompiler

  • java.lang.Object
    • net.sourceforge.waters.model.base.DefaultProxyVisitor
      • net.sourceforge.waters.model.module.DefaultModuleProxyVisitor
        • net.sourceforge.waters.model.compiler.instance.ModuleInstanceCompiler
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    net.sourceforge.waters.model.analysis.Abortable, ProxyVisitor, ModuleProxyVisitor

    public class ModuleInstanceCompiler
extends DefaultModuleProxyVisitor
implements net.sourceforge.waters.model.analysis.Abortable

    A compiler tool to expand bindings, foreach blocks, and instantiations in a module.

    The instance compiler accepts a module (ModuleProxy) as input and produces another module as output. It expands all aliases, foreach constructs, and instantiations. Event arrays as well as component and variable arrays are enumerated explicitly. Variable components are preserved in the output, with all guards and actions simplified by substituting values obtained from aliasing or instantiation.

    It is ensured that the resultant module only contains objects of the following types:

    • EventDeclProxy, where only simple events are defined, i.e., the list of ranges is guaranteed to be empty;
    • SimpleComponentProxy;
    • VariableComponentProxy.
    • ConstantAliasProxy, if the input module uses enumeration types. A single named constant called ":atoms" including all enumeration atoms in the input module may be declared in the output. If there are no enumerations, then the output module contains no aliases whatsoever.

    The instance compiler is used as the first stage of the ModuleCompiler to translate a ModuleProxy into a ProductDESProxy, but it can also be used as a stand-alone component to remove foreach blocks and instantiation from a module. To do so, the user first creates an instance of this class and configures it as needed. Then compilation is started using the compile() or compile(List) method, which returns the instantiated module. The following code can be used to instantiate a given module.

    try {
      ModuleProxyFactory factory = ModuleElementFactory.getInstance();
      OperatorTable optable = CompilerOperatorTable.getInstance();
      ProxyUnmarshaller<ModuleProxy> unmarshaller = new JAXBModuleMarshaller(factory, optable);
      DocumentManager manager = new DocumentManager();
      manager.registerUnmarshaller(unmarshaller);
      ModuleInstanceCompiler compiler = new ModuleInstanceCompiler(manager, factory, module);
      // configure compiler here if needed ...
      ModuleProxy instantiatedModule = compiler.compile();
      // instantiation successful, result in instantiatedModule ...
    } catch (EvalException exception) {
      // module has errors ...
    } catch (JAXBException | SAXException exception) {
      // error setting up XML parsers - should not happen ...
    }

    Author:
    Robi Malik, Roger Su

      • compile

        public ModuleProxy compile(List<ParameterBindingProxy> bindings)
                    throws EvalException
        Instantiates the input module using the given parameter bindings.
        Parameters:
        bindings - List of parameter bindings to supply values for parameters specified in the module. A module's event declarations (EventDeclProxy) and constant alias declarations (ConstantAliasProxy) may be declared as parameters, in which case the bindings can be used to supply values to replace these parameters.
        Returns:
        The instantiated module.
        Throws:
        EvalException - to indicate any syntactical or semantical errors encountered during compilation.

      • setEnabledPropertyNames

        public void setEnabledPropertyNames(Collection<String> names)
        Sets the set of enabled property names. If non-null, the compiler will check all property components to be generated (automata of type ComponentKind.PROPERTY) against the names in this collection, and suppress any that are not listed. The default for this option is null, which means to include all properties in the output.

        public void setEnabledPropositionNames(Collection<String> names)
        If non-null, the compiler will check all proposition events to be generated (events of type EventKind.PROPOSITION) against the names in this collection, and suppress any that are not listed. The default for this option is null, which means to include all propositions in the output.
